  "text": "It is well known that cirrus clouds play a critical role in the radiation balance of the earth, and thus an accurate treatment of their radiative properties is needed. The modified anomalous diffraction approximation (MADA) has been used to treat ice cloud radiative properties in global climate models (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and in satellite remote sensing (e.g., [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , but has thus far undergone only limited testing. The MADA does not predict the scattering phase function of an ice particle and thus cannot calculate the asymmetry parameter, g. Rather, parameterizations of g are often combined with MADA to produce a comprehensive treatment of optical properties, such as the scheme described in [CITATION_5] . This study was con-ducted to provide more extensive testing of MADA and also to compare MADA with other cirrus cloud radiation schemes.",
